<Page x:Class="AsynAwaitExamples.Steps.Step13_ValueTask"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:AsynAwaitExamples.ViewModels"
      Title="Step 13 - ValueTask">
    <Page.DataContext>
        <vm:Step13ViewModel/>
    </Page.DataContext>
    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
        <StackPanel Margin="10">
            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource HeaderStyle}" 
                       Text="Step 13: ValueTask and ValueTask&lt;T&gt;"/>

            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource ExplanationStyle}" xml:space="preserve">VALUETASK: A lightweight alternative to Task that avoids heap allocations.

Task&lt;T&gt; always creates an object on the heap, even if the result is
already available (like returning a cached value). For hot paths called
millions of times, this creates garbage collection pressure.

ValueTask&lt;T&gt; is a struct. When the result is already available, it
wraps the value directly with no heap allocation at all! When async work
IS needed, it falls back to wrapping a real Task internally.

WHEN TO USE: Methods that frequently return synchronously (caches, pools).
WHEN NOT TO USE: When you need Task.WhenAll, need to await multiple times,
or when the method almost always does real async work.</TextBlock>

            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="Compare Task&lt;T&gt; vs ValueTask&lt;T&gt; allocations"
                    Command="{Binding CompareAllocationsCommand}"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="Cache miss -- falls back to async"
                    Command="{Binding CacheMissCommand}"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="Show ValueTask rules"
                    Command="{Binding ShowRulesCommand}"/>

            <TextBox Style="{StaticResource OutputStyle}" Height="300"
                     Text="{Binding OutputText, Mode=OneWay}"/>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
